      <!-- MEASURE -->
      <section class="card" aria-labelledby="measureTitle">
        <h2 id="measureTitle">How to Measure Your Dog's Neck</h2>
        <div class="grid-2">
          <div>
            <div class="steps" role="list">
              <div class="step" role="listitem">
                <strong>1. Tools</strong>
                <ol>
                  <li>Soft cloth measuring tape (preferred) or a string + ruler.</li>
                </ol>
              </div>
              <div class="step" role="listitem">
                <strong>2. Position</strong>
                <ol>
                  <li>Measure <strong>high on the neck</strong>, directly behind the ears and under the jawline — this is the working position for prong collars.</li>
                </ol>
              </div>
              <div class="step" role="listitem">
                <strong>3. Snug fit</strong>
                <ol>
                  <li>The tape should be snug but not tight — just enough so it won’t slip. Record the measurement in inches.</li>
                </ol>
              </div>
              <div class="step" role="listitem">
                <strong>4. Match size</strong>
                <ol>
                  <li>Use the chart on the right to choose your collar size. When in doubt, choose the next size up for thick-coated breeds.</li>
                </ol>
              </div>
            </div>
            <p class="note">Tip: If your dog has loose skin or a deep coat, press the coat down at the measuring point to get an accurate neck circumference.</p>
          </div>

          <div>
            <table aria-label="Sizing chart">
              <thead>
                <tr><th>Neck Circumference (in)</th><th>Recommended Collar Size</th></tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr><td>10 – 12 in</td><td>Small</td></tr>
                <tr><td>12 – 14 in</td><td>Small/Medium</td></tr>
                <tr><td>14 – 16 in</td><td>Medium</td></tr>
                <tr><td>16 – 18 in</td><td>Medium/Large</td></tr>
                <tr><td>18 – 20 in</td><td>Large</td></tr>
                <tr><td>20 – 24 in</td><td>Extra Large</td></tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>

            <p class="note"><strong>Sizing considerations:</strong> These are general guidelines — check the collar product page on Amazon for exact link counts and size-specific specs. If your measurement falls exactly on the boundary, choose the larger size for comfort.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- FIT & USE -->
      <section class="card" aria-labelledby="useTitle">
        <h2 id="useTitle">How to Fit & Use Your Prong Collar — Safety First</h2>

        <div style="display:grid;gap:12px;">
          <div class="warn" role="alert">
            Important safety reminder: Prong collars are training tools and must be used responsibly. <strong>Never</strong> leave a prong collar on an unattended dog. Do not use constant pressure, and consult a certified trainer or veterinarian if unsure.
          </div>

          <div>
            <h3 style="margin:6px 0;">Fitting Instructions (step-by-step)</h3>
            <ol>
              <li><strong>Assemble</strong> the collar per the product instructions. The collar should sit high on the neck, just behind the ears, with the prong ends facing inward toward the dog's neck.</li>
              <li><strong>Size for snugness:</strong> The collar should be snug enough that it won't slide down to the throat. It should not be so tight that it constricts breathing.</li>
              <li><strong>Attach leash:</strong> Clip the leash to the live D-ring (the ring intended for training corrections). Do not attach to safety clips used only for holding the collar closed during storage.</li>
              <li><strong>Short corrections:</strong> Use quick, gentle corrections — not continuous pulling. The goal is a reminder, not pain or prolonged pressure.</li>
              <li><strong>Supervision & time:</strong> Use the collar only during short training or walking sessions. Remove for play, sleep, or unsupervised periods.</li>
            </ol>
          </div>

          <div>
            <h3 style="margin:6px 0;">Best Practices</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>Combine prong collar use with reward-based training for best results.</li>
              <li>Keep sessions short (5–10 minutes) and end on a positive note.</li>
              <li>Check collar fit and prongs regularly for damage or wear.</li>
              <li>If your dog shows signs of distress, stop and consult a professional.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

